segments.text: This is such a beautiful morning.
I can't thank my maker for sparing me this day.
You know, as we grow older,
Don't take time, or probably, I wouldn't say as we grow older, I say as we're younger people, we don't take time to say how great it is to wake up in the morning and see the sunrise.
We take it for granted.
But in reality, the man above has the time clock.
And to some of us, that clock is soon to run out.
But I want the world to know that I enjoy my life and all of my friends.
As I set out this morning on my little porch, my home, it was the greatest experience that I have ever witnessed, or one of the greatest, I will say that.
I had always been under the impression that a chaparral
or a road runner or a persona, whatever you want to call it, made its nest on the ground.
But to my great surprise, it doesn't.
And I sat there and I watched that mother bring her two babies down the tree and across the highway and over on

vacant lot it was the greatest thing that I can tell you that ever was she got to the edge of the tree she raised her tail three times and whatever noise you want to say she made whether it was with her bill or with her voice box as you know the persona call as well as I she made that call
a couple of times.
Now just twice, not three times.
But she raised the tail three times.
Those little birds came tripping down that tree.
How?
I'm sure they helped with their claws.
And she stood at the root of the tree until they were down.
She took them out on the flat and
Sure, there was grasshoppers, there was bugs, and they were fed.
When she got to the highway, she walked to the edge of it.
She raised that tail again three times.
She gave a couple of calls, whether it was with her bill, I don't know, or how, but you know the persona call.
And these little toots came up to the side of the road
And they ran.
They didn't just trip, but they ran across that road.
And she hopped across on the other side.
She got up on the top.
She went right up the cut in this Dobie flat, which was at least three and a half to four feet high.
She stood up there.
She raised that tail three times.
She gave that call.
She looked from one side to the other.
She looked to the east, to the west, to the north.
And she gave the call a second time.
And let me tell you, those little birds came up that high embankment and right to her feet.
To me, where else?
can a person but the hill country sit and watch anything any more lovely than that.
Yes, she was training her babies to look to the right, to the left, and then make your move.
She popped that bill a couple of times, and every one of them came to her
It's just like they were standing at attention.
And she came down the trail to where she had been fed before.
And we had pitched out some bread.
She took it in her beak.
The babies didn't come.
Now, they didn't come down that trail.
She took it in her beak and took it back over and fed them.
Well, at the end of the third day, the babies came.
And she brought them with the same precaution across the highway and took them back.
The training of even a bird begins in infancy.
You forget, mothers and fathers,
I know from actual experience that a mother's touch and a mother's love and a mother's intuition means more than any babysitter could ever mean.
No one can look back on life and remember it like they can at
as they can, kneeling at the side of their mother in prayer at evening, or hearing her lullabies to put them to sleep at night.
I know that I am one of the most fortunate people in the world.
Yes, one of the poorest, but one of the richest when it comes to God's own handiwork.
My mother had the most beautiful soprano voice, my father a beautiful tenor voice.
They had time to sing to us when we wanted to hear it.
They had time to tell us stories at night.
They had time to tuck us in because we had more time than we had money.
We had more time to spend at home than we had
to go somewhere because we didn't have the money to put the gas in old Betsy to go.
Those were days that was molding of a character.
I had a friend here today that is several years older than I, but one that knows the history of the hill country.
backwards, forwards, upside down, and crossways.
I had forgotten a lot of the things that he reminded me of.
I well remember riding in races when I wasn't over 12 years old.
Race race, horse races.
And it didn't excite me.
I enjoyed it.
Could you see?
Can you think of a girl today getting out and doing things like that?
Well, that was the thing that we did for entertainment.
Rope, ride, tell stories, kick the can, see who was the fastest to do this or who could jump the furthest, who could high jump the highest and all of that.
That was all we had to do.
was our own skills.
But that makes life worth living and look back on today.
Those people who competed with us, I look back today.
They're doctors, nurses, schoolteachers.
In other words, they are the salt of the earth.
and they were brought up in the hill country.
I want the world to know that there's not a smarter man that ever walked out of the Johnson City High School.
Now that was just a little too before school but we put out mighty good people and Emmett Redford
Dr. Emmett Redford, I should say, is one of the best educated.
All right, we'll have Dr. Revity Glidden.
Let me tell you, these people were the salt of the earth, and they worked, and they worked hard to get what they had because they didn't have the money handed down to them.
And they really put out to get what they had.
Not only did we produce presidents, but we have produced just as many good lay people.
And they all have roots down in the hill country.
No trabaje tanto.

Today, the fifth day of September, 1981, Corky and I went down to the ranch to take an inventory of the cattle that we had and how old they were, which ones we should dispose of, which ones we should keep.
Honestly, I know that people hearing this or reading it will not believe it.
But it's true, folks.
We have some cattle down there that are crossbreds, Angus and Bramers, that are 20 years old.
They are in the best shape.
Fat?
Yes.
have the finest calves on them that we have ever produced.
But I told Corky, I said, Corky, to me, it definitely is a risk

To go through another winter with cattle this old it's time that we sold them, even though you don't get too much for them, they have served their time they've served their purpose and they like other folks or people are.
beyond their productive years.
However, I will say this.
They have produced the best calf crop this year that I have ever seen.
I don't know whether it is
the breed, the cross, or whether it is the grassland on which they graze.
I have often said, and I've heard my daddy say it, I've heard Sid Hyatt, and I've heard Harvey Croft, Armand Ware, and my Uncle Jay say any time that you can get a granite, gravel,
piece of land the grass on it has more minerals and is stronger than any grass that can grow in the hill country.
That I believe with all my heart because that's exactly what we have on our place and that's exactly why these cows are in such good shape.
I have a little
framer bull down there that I call Little Bull.
I can stand on the car and blow the horn and say, come on, Little Bull.
He's only a year old and he'll come running off of that hill just for me to love him and pet him and scratch his ears, scratch around his horn, scratch around his tail.
I can touch him on his four legs and say, get down, brother.
I can't reach up here.
What does he do?
He lays down.
Now, I'm telling you, if you know anything about Bremer cattle, you know that they've got to know you and know you love them, or they're not going to do it.
And listen, he is one of the best.
And to me, that's what life is all about.
Corky said, well, I've just got to sell these.
I don't know what else to do.
I said, give me time, Corky.
I don't want this one to go to market.
because he would mean a lot to somebody as a herd bull.
Let me put him on the trading post as an advertisement.
If nothing else, I'll take him to town and stake him in my front yard and show people what he can do, and I won't have any trouble selling him.
So I sold him on the idea.
So
It won't be long until you'll see a Bremer bull out in my front yard.
And I hope to be able to show the world what he can do.
And I'm proud of him.
Now that's just a small accomplishment.
That's just a small thing in life.
But to me, that's living.
Letting the animals
Know that you love them.
And just like this morning, I was sitting out in the front reading my newspaper about 6.30, and I had the porch light on.
Wasn't but a few minutes till...

in jumps bunny bunks a squirrel in the tree and I've never heard such barking and scolding in my life and that was no other reason but I had the porch light on and sitting in the port in my chair on the porch reading the paper I said bunks if you'll come around the back door I'll feed you and hush that chattering well in a few minutes I could hear
Bunny bunks going over the roof.
Well, of course, I went to the back and fed it.
I didn't want it eating out in the front because, sure enough, they do.
They make a mess, and I wasn't anxious to sweep it up and clean it.
But I'm proud to know that the squirrels even love me.
And that's something else.
I have a mockingbird that comes, and I feed it.
I love to hear them sing.
In fact,
I don't know of anything that God has created in this world that there isn't some good in and put here for some purpose.
Purpose we may not understand.
We may not know.
But God only made good things.
He didn't make anything bad.
The only thing that's made bad, we did it ourselves.
And I love to see the sunrise come up in the east, and I love to watch it go down in the west, and hope that he will spare my life to see it come up in the morning.
He would say, adios, mi amigos.
Of all the great experiences that a child can have is living with nature and seeing it firsthand.

If you've ever witnessed a mother raccoon teaching her babies how to fish that's one of the most interesting things in this world you'll understand exactly how mothers of today work and do the same with their children.
Uncle Sid Hyde was one of the greatest naturalists that this country will ever know, yet he was just a regular fella.
He said, now if you want to see how this is done, sister, sit down back here behind this rock just where you can be tall enough to look over and see what she did.
The old mother raccoon went down to the river
And she walked up and down the bank and she looked and she could see that there were some little perch in this shallow water.
She came back and she chattered and chattered and chattered to these four baby raccoons.
And she took them one at a time down to this shallow pool.
And she got in.
And she called to them, and one at a time got in this water, just one.
And the other sat on the bank.
And she would take them around and she'd paddle them around and she would talk to them.

She'd take, when they got out, she just took it by her two front feet and just more or less shook the water off of him, set him down and just chattered as if to say, now you sit right here and don't you move till I tell you to.
And sure enough, that little old fella sat there
and waited until each one had had a chance at trying to catch the fish.
Definitely, the second one she took in the water did catch its fish.
Well, each one would go back in and she would repeat the same thing.
When she got through fishing, or they'd all had their turn, she went to each one of them
And she picked them up and shook them real good to see that the water was getting off of their fur.
She set them back down.
And she sat down just on her hunkers, more or less, and chattered and chattered, just as if to say, now, this is your first lesson, and this is how it's done.
We're going to deeper water.
So up the river they went about.
25 yards, and Uncle Sid saw her going up the path, and these little coons followed one right behind the other.
She got up there in the same procedure.
She didn't take the one she took the first time, but she took the one that went in last.
She took him that time.
And it's quite amusing.
She took him and spent a lot more time in training him
than she did in the beginning.
For what reason, unless it was that he was quite smaller than the others or was weaker, I guess that was it.
He was the weaker of the four.
That happens in all families, even you know that as well as I, that the mother will favor the weaker child each time.
It even comes out in our animal life.
Anyway, she gave them all the things.
But it was the cutest thing.
It took two of them to catch this catfish.
It wasn't much more than a foot long.
But to them, it was a great big one.
And it took both of them.
And they put it out on that rock.
And let me tell you.
They all four ate, and there wasn't any fussing about, that's mine, you don't get any.
They all four sat down around that catfish, and they'd just take a bite, it looked like, and then the next one take a bite around.
And the old mother sat and watched just as faithful as a mother at a table would while his children ate.
To me, that's the most wonderful lesson that a person could think of.
Those things are, that's something that's never written up in books.
People don't take the time they take for granted that everyone knows how it's done.
And let me tell you, you've always heard that a possum plays dead, and he's called old pouty possum.
But honestly, he isn't dead, but he's in a dead faint.
He actually faints, and that's what really happens.
And people have the wrong concept of it.
And let me tell you, that's another thing that is really cute.
Just watch an old mother possum.
She'll take her tail and stretch it out.
And one little possum will get with his head to the right and the other with his head to the left.
And that's the way she'll do it.
And that old tail goes over her back.
And each little possum will.
hook his claws in her fur and she'll carry him and she'll just go just a hopping.
She doesn't run.
She more or less hops down the trail to wherever she's going to take these babies and she'll chatter or grunt more or less and
If either of the little fellas see something strange, they give this little call of caution.
And she will stop and she'll look.
She'll look to the right and she'll look to the left.
And then she'll go on.
And if something is wrong, she'll leave the trail and take to the bushes.
And they're cute.
You know, one day we were riding in the pasture, and I kept seeing this old buzzard that was just sitting on this dead tree, right on the tip top on a dead tree.
And I said to my daddy, I said, Daddy, do you reckon it could be a dead cow over there in that thicket?
I see a buzzard sitting over there.
And he said, No, darling.
He says, I don't think so.
He said, If it's a dead animal, there would be several.
buzzards all flying around together.
But just this one, and I have an idea that there's a buzzard nest there.
I said, a buzzard nest?
He said, yes, you know, they lay eggs and they'll hatch them and one will stay and watch and the other one will go for food.
And I said, Daddy, take me over there and let's see.
And he said, now let me tell you.
I'll take you over there, and if the old mama buzzard is on the nest, that will be the papa buzzard that's watching, and he'll have to go out and get feed for her, and he'll come back and feed her.
But don't, now let me tell you, sister, I mean this.
Don't ever go up to that nest and try to bother those little birds if they're there or pick them up.
I said, well, why?
Why can't I pick them up?
I did know, and he told me when I was a child not to ever put my hand in a little bird's nest that their mama wouldn't come back.
We left a scent that would frighten them, and they wouldn't come back, and the baby birds would starve.
Well, I didn't figure that by picking up one of these little buzzards that that was bothering.
He said, no, don't touch those buzzards.
Leave them alone.
If you do, you'll be sorry.
And I said, well, why, Daddy, why?
He said, well, that old papa buzzard, well, he didn't say vomit.
He said, he'll just puke all over you and say, you just never will get that scent off of you.
And I said, oh, Daddy, I wouldn't let that happen to me.
I'd get out of his way.
He said, well, you better not do it.
Just mind what I tell you.
Leave it alone.
We looked at these two little buzzards, and they were...
Little yellow downy things reminded me of little goslings, and oh, I thought they were the cutest things that ever was.
Well, every two or three days, I'd have to go back and look at the buzzards, but I still didn't touch them.
Well, they turned to be white.
And, oh, I thought that was so pretty.
And so Emmett Redford, Dr. Emmett Redford at the University of Texas in Linden and Kitty Clyde and Georgie Kamak and Irene, oh, just a whole gang of us after Sunday school was there.
And I said, let's go down and look at the little buzzards.
And they said, oh, little buzzards.
I don't guess I ever saw one.
Well, when we got down there this time, they had turned to another color.
And they were kind of a...

brown looking and just like a argancic turkey and color brown and I thought my goodness saliva but this is where they always were and I know it's the same buzzards and Margaret said well now the last time we was down here they were white they wasn't like this and I said no they've changed color so we went on back and we didn't bother them next time we went down there they were kind of uh
Well.
A green it was just nothing I couldn't say, but just a kind of a dark.
Dirty.

green look more or less like an olive green and I said well I've never seen anything like that now that just beats the world and we went on back and I told my daddy and he said oh yes they'll have it they'll change color again before they get black and I said daddy I just don't believe that that's the same buzzards I don't believe they're buzzards I think there's something else well it was quite a curiosity we went back down there in about another week and they were uh
They turned to almost a black, but the most beautiful iridescent color that I ever looked at in my life.
And I decided, and they were hopping around, just hopping and hopping all around, but not able to fly.
And Margaret...
said to me, said, Ava, why don't you go in there and get one of those, and let's just see if it is a buzzard.
I said, well, how could we tell anymore if it's a buzzard just by looking at it out here?
And she said, well, we can look at its feet.
I said, well, you can see its feet anyway.
She said, well, let's go in there and get one.
So we started in there, and I'm telling you, that old papa buzzard really did, just like my daddy said, he sure did puke on us.
stink and we vomited and we vomited.
We were just sicker than a dog from the scent.
And got home, and my mother wouldn't let us come in the house.
And we went out and turned the water on out under the tank at the well to wash.
But oh my God, trying to get it out of our hair.
I'll never forget, and we both had long hair.
And I'll tell you, we were the biggest mess that ever was.
But I learned my lesson and learned it fast, not to bother little buzzards.
